post_text:
KMS Football vs. Cimarron Results

7th grade lost 8-2.
A hard-fought game with multiple opportunities to score points. A goal-line stand early in the game by Cimarron and a touchdown on the last play called back due to a penalty. The effort was great with the team facing many obstacles this week.

8th grade lost 44-22
KMS fought back after a large halftime deficit. This team also experienced many obstacles this week.

Next Week's Game is at Scott City.

post_text: Wow Time really flies when you are having fun. June 30th will be our last day of Summer Lunch Rocks service. I would like to tell you the students, parents and the community THANK YOU for all the support. Susan Anthony, Lori Munsell, Michelle Ewalt and all of the kitchen staff want you to know that we are so happy that we have been able to serve you everyday. Susan and Lori have been so excited to see all of you on a daily basis, Michelle and Harley have looked forward to serving nutritious meals to all students at weightlifting. We have truly enjoyed serving all the students and community since March. Thank you for all of the support. We look forward to seeing you all in August!!!

May 22, 2020

KSHSAA's Statement on Preparticipation Physical Exams (PPE) for 2020-2021 School Year

The KSHSAA Sports Medicine Advisory Committee met on May 20 to consider potential modification of the requirement of the annual Pre-Participation Physical Exam. Following extended discussion, a review of literature, and a geographic check of each represented area relative to local health care access, the committee supported a motion to maintain the current practice and require ‚Äúnew‚Äù Pre-Participant Physical Exam for every athletic and spirit participant.

All student-athletes are required to get a new Pre-Participation Physical Exam for the 2020-21 school year.

shared_text:
Guy Charles - Financial Services Professional at MassMutual
April 19 at 3:51 PM ¬∑

Another simple card game for kids!
HOW TO PLAY üê∑PIGüê∑

üòúIf you want to be notified when more games post, please like üëçüèº and follow my page.üòã

Rules:
Shuffle the cards. Deal until each player has four cards.

The aim of the game is to collect four of a kind. Players must choose what they want to collect and discard. The discarded card is passed to the player on their left who also discards a card to the next player on their left and so on.

Once a player has collected four of a kind, the player must immediately put a finger on their nose.

If another player sees them do this, they too put a finger on their nose even if they don't have four of a kind. The last player to notice the others and place a finger on their nose gets the letter ‚ÄúP‚Äù given to them.

The first player to receive all three letters: P, I, G, is eliminated. The last player in play is the winner.

KMS: Create, Connect, Recharge, Reflect
March 30 at 2:38 PM ¬∑

Hi everyone!

Mr. Hammond here, hoping you are doing well and healthy. Since we can't meet together to sing, I thought I would try having us all sing in our own homes! Each week on Friday I will be hosting a live-streamed sing-along with songs about a certain theme.

This weeks theme: Support
Bill Withers - Lean On Me
Bruno Mars - Count On Me

https://open.spotify.com/playlist/7eJ3u75SWcfJBXjZtIsrv6

We'll talk a little bit about each, get some education in there, but mostly just enjoy the idea of singing along with someone, even when we're separated by houses. The songs I'm going to be singing are on this playlist, so you can listen to them and learn them for Friday! Keep an eye on this space for more information and share this with anyone you think would enjoy it. I hope to hear you then!

STUDENT OF THE MONTH-February

The February Student of the Month for Kepley Middle School was Natalie Rubio-Acosta (8th grade), daughter of Maria Acosta and Jorge Luna. Her favorite sport is basketball. She also participates in volleyball, tack, and Scholars Bowl at KMS. In her spare time she makes and sells cake pops, bracelets, and other crafty items. She loves spending time with her family.

Students who receive this honor our first nominated by KMS Staff using the common core beliefs of KMS as a guide. Respect of everyone in and outside of KMS, student's academics, and the student using the opportunities given to be successful.

Congrats to Natalie Rubio-Acosta!

The movie is rated PG13. It does contain some inappropriate language.

post_text:
Kepley Cub Wrestling

It was a great day of wrestling for our KMS cub wrestling team at the Dodge City Dual Wrestling Tournament on Saturday.

KMS defeated Dodge City Comanche 57-51.
KMS defeated Garden City - Ken Henderson 54-48.

This advanced KMS to the Championship round vs. Great Bend and Liberal Eisenhower to guarantee a top three finish. Each team had to dual one another.

KMS defeated a very tough Great Bend team in the Championship round 51-50.
Liberal Eisenhower defeated KMS in a very competitive dual 60-52.

Due to how the tie breaking points criteria was set up (due to a 3-way tie), KMS finished 3rd place out of nine teams

Below is a link to some pictures that were taken at the tournament.

https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/164fs8FserlJ9bI7xqK7Gwli-EzXLNQ67Mu9CGwulDM8/edit?usp=sharing

STUDENT OF THE MONTH-October

The October Student of the Month for Kepley Middle School was Katelynn Rice (8th grade), daughter of Ryan and Megan Rice. She works on various projects through Cimarron 4-H. In sports she plays volleyball for SW Attack. At KMS she plays in volleyball, basketball, and track.

Students who receive this honor our first nominated by KMS Staff using the common core beliefs of KMS as a guide. Respect of everyone in and outside of KMS, student's academics, and student using the opportunities given to be successful. After 3 are chosen as finalists, everyone at KMS votes.

Congrats to Katelynn Rice!
